        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date>M&#39;ch 15&#47;54</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd I. Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Friend&#8212;</p>
			<p>I am in Receipt of your Letter of the<lb/> <date>3d</date> ulto and also of the Books&#44; which were<lb/> all in good order. Owing to the<lb/> accident to the steamer Georgia&#44; which<lb/> connected with the steamer Columbia<lb/> on this side by which I received the<lb/> Books&#44; and the annual long passage<lb/> of the Columbia&#44; I did not receive the<lb/> Books till a few days ago&#59; and<lb/> therefore I could not as yet distribute<lb/> the Books which have been ordered&#59; but<lb/> after this Mail Steamer is gone I shall<lb/> attend to. I have sold several D. Setters&#44;<lb/> and I have not doubt with those Books<lb/> which are not ordered&#44; I can meet<lb/> with a ready sale&#44; as the Books<lb/> are all got up in a Neat &#38; handsome<lb/> manner. The &#8220;Hebrew Benevolent<lb/> Ball&#8221; of which I made mention in<lb/> my previous Letter&#44; has come of night</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>before last&#59; a very large assemblage was<lb/> present&#44; &#38; the profit at present estimated<lb/> will be about &#36;1500&#59; really the Ball was<lb/> an honour to the Jews here&#44; and creditable to<lb/> the managers&#59; everything passed of to the<lb/> satisfaction of all present&#59; one unusual<lb/> feature of the Ball was the large<lb/> number of Ladies&#44; which numbered to<lb/> about 200. It is due to our Jewish po&#45;<lb/>&#45;pulation to say&#44; that a great number of our<lb/> persuasion are very much respected as<lb/> first class &#38; prominent citizens.</p>
			<p><persName>Mr. Cohen</persName> has been to see me &#38; told me a<lb/> great deal of the China&#45;Jews&#44; but as he<lb/> has given you already much Information<lb/> in that regard&#44; &#38; as he told me he would<lb/> write to you again by next mail&#44; it<lb/> would be fore me unnecessary to say any&#45;<lb/>&#45;thing upon that subject. I think you<lb/> would have done wise if you would have<lb/> advertised in your Occident&#44; that your<lb/> Books could be had by me. I am<lb/> well acquainted with <persName>Mr. Chay Emanuel</persName>&#44;<lb/> &#38; he requests me to give his Regards to you.<lb/> <persName>Mrs &#38; Mr. Roggenburger</persName> wish kindly to be<lb/> remembered to you. With my best wishes for<lb/> your good Health &#38; Prosperity I remain yours Truly</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">Cauffman H. Meyer</persName></p>
			<p rend="The following is written sideways in the left margin">The enclosed Notice I have cut out from the &#8220;daily California Chronicle&#8221;<lb/> all papers unite in speaking highly of the Ball.</p>
          
        </body>
